</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="37" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
NORWAY. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sør-Trøndelag">Sor-Trondelag</normalizedToken>
: Oppdal municipality, Drivdalen, by the rapids in the lower part of the river Kaldvella, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="62" direction="north" minutes="17" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="62.283333">62°17'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="9" direction="east" minutes="35" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="9.583333">9°35'E</geoCoordinate>
, alt. 940-980 m, exposed rock face in the subalpine region. 23 July 1993, E. Timdal 7535 (O L-125!), TLC: rangiformic acid, norrangiformic acid, unknown substances.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">New to Sweden.</emphasis>
The species was previously known only from Norway and Greenland (
<bibRefCitation author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
). It resembles the more common 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aglaea" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" rank="species" species="aglaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">C. aglaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sommerf.) Hafellner, but differs in forming white areolae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Calvitimela perlata (O L- 195661). Scale: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64929" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">4</figureCitation>
), slightly longer ascospores 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="38" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
11.5-17 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
), and in the presence of rangiformic and norrangiformic acids in the thallus. In 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aglaea" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" rank="species" species="aglaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">C. aglaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the areolae are usually pale yellow, the ascospores shorter (9-13.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
), and the thallus contains atranorin, bourgeanic acid, usnic acid (rarely lacking), and sometimes stictic acid (
<bibRefCitation author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973734" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64929" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Figure 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Sant" authorityYear="2004" baseAuthorityName="Haugan &amp; Timdal" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Mycoblastaceae" genus="Calvitimela" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Calvitimela perlata" order="Lecanorales" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="perlata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Calvitimela perlata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(O L-195661). Scale: 5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="38">In Norway, the species grows on sun-exposed, more or less sloping rock surfaces, often where water is trickling or near rivers or waterfalls in the subalpine and alpine regions. The Swedish locality is a boulder in the alpine region.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="38" type="specimen examined">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Specimen examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
SWEDEN. Torne Lappmark: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Låktatjåkka">Laktatjakka</normalizedToken>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="68" direction="north" minutes="24.87" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="68.4145">68°24.87'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="18" direction="east" minutes="19.07" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="18.317833">18°19.07'E</geoCoordinate>
, alt. 640 m, steep face of boulder in the low alpine region. 8 July 2014, Timdal 13464-1 (O L-195661), TLC: rangiformic acid (major). norrangiformic acid (minor), unknown substances (minor).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
